1
00:00:07,250 --> 00:00:09,760
"Police Department"

2
00:00:38,660 --> 00:00:40,160
But was that really true,

3
00:00:40,160 --> 00:00:41,560
what you said before?

4
00:01:41,160 --> 00:01:43,660
"First Investigation Division"

5
00:01:44,960 --> 00:01:47,060
That's definitely what he said.

6
00:01:47,060 --> 00:01:48,460
Maybe he's mistaken.

7
00:01:50,370 --> 00:01:51,570
In that case...

8
00:01:53,740 --> 00:01:54,840
She's here.

9
00:02:05,750 --> 00:02:09,550
The three suspects Suwa, Yoshioka, Asai...

10
00:02:09,550 --> 00:02:12,350
There's a possibility that there're other accomplices?

11
00:02:21,260 --> 00:02:22,360
What?

12
00:02:27,640 --> 00:02:30,040
Is anything on my face?

13
00:02:31,740 --> 00:02:34,840
What is it?

14
00:02:36,950 --> 00:02:38,850
Excuse me.

15
00:02:38,850 --> 00:02:39,850
It's nothing.

16
00:02:39,850 --> 00:02:41,850
What on earth?

17
00:02:41,850 --> 00:02:44,450
What're you all doing looking at me

18
00:02:44,450 --> 00:02:46,550
and whispering away?

19
00:02:46,550 --> 00:02:48,860
No, it's nothing.

20
00:02:48,860 --> 00:02:50,260
Right?

21
00:02:50,260 --> 00:02:51,460
Yes.

22
00:02:51,460 --> 00:02:53,160
No, it's nothing.

23
00:02:56,460 --> 00:03:00,640
No. It's nothing. Right?

24
00:03:00,640 --> 00:03:02,240
Don't worry about it.

25
00:03:07,440 --> 00:03:08,640
Really?

26
00:03:10,350 --> 00:03:12,150
Yes.

27
00:03:17,950 --> 00:03:21,760
Questioning of the victims of the Haidocho case is done.

28
00:03:23,660 --> 00:03:25,860
Yes...

29
00:03:25,860 --> 00:03:28,260
As to that case...

30
00:03:29,860 --> 00:03:31,270
Give me a break.

31
00:03:34,740 --> 00:03:37,640
I'm amazing, don't you agree?

32
00:03:37,640 --> 00:03:39,240
Really.

33
00:03:39,240 --> 00:03:42,740
I mean, talk about spitting it out!

34
00:03:45,450 --> 00:03:47,850
It was like a scene from a drama.

35
00:03:47,850 --> 00:03:51,350
He says he wants to eat pork cutlet and stuff.

36
00:03:51,350 --> 00:03:52,650
What...

37
00:03:54,760 --> 00:03:56,860
Takagi...

38
00:03:56,860 --> 00:03:59,160
What... what's wrong?

39
00:03:59,160 --> 00:04:00,660
What do you mean by that?

40
00:04:01,860 --> 00:04:05,370
Why didn't you tell us what was going on too?

41
00:04:05,370 --> 00:04:07,240
Right, Takagi!

42
00:04:08,140 --> 00:04:09,340
You know,

43
00:04:09,340 --> 00:04:12,840
we've got to prepare our hearts for it too, Takagi!

44
00:04:12,840 --> 00:04:15,540
What? Prepare your hearts?

45
00:04:15,540 --> 00:04:17,950
What is this preparing your hearts about?

46
00:04:17,950 --> 00:04:20,350
Ta... Takagi!

47
00:04:20,350 --> 00:04:21,850
Enough.

48
00:04:21,850 --> 00:04:24,050
So, Takagi...

49
00:04:24,050 --> 00:04:25,650
Yes?

50
00:04:25,650 --> 00:04:28,160
It's you, isn't it?

51
00:04:29,360 --> 00:04:33,160
You mean the case the Inspector Megure is talking about on the phone?

52
00:04:33,160 --> 00:04:34,660
Officer Takagi.

53
00:04:34,660 --> 00:04:36,970
You can be very funny!

54
00:04:36,970 --> 00:04:39,070
About Officer Sato...

55
00:04:41,440 --> 00:04:42,440
Yes.

56
00:04:42,440 --> 00:04:43,440
You see,

57
00:04:43,440 --> 00:04:45,540
the stuff that's glittering on Officer Sato's finger...

58
00:04:48,340 --> 00:04:50,450
Ran, what's up?

59
00:04:50,450 --> 00:04:52,250
That ring...

60
00:04:52,250 --> 00:04:53,950
The ring.

61
00:04:55,350 --> 00:04:57,350
Ring?

62
00:04:57,350 --> 00:04:58,750
Ring.

63
00:05:00,560 --> 00:05:03,160
You're right.

64
00:05:03,160 --> 00:05:05,560
The ring...

65
00:05:05,560 --> 00:05:07,960
What? Ring?

66
00:05:07,960 --> 00:05:10,670
It's a ring I've never seen before.

67
00:05:10,670 --> 00:05:13,370
Moreover, he's wearing it on her left ring finger?

68
00:05:13,370 --> 00:05:16,440
Who... who on earth did she get it from?

69
00:05:17,440 --> 00:05:19,740
Cool it, cool head!

70
00:05:19,740 --> 00:05:22,740
What's needed is composure. Calm down.

71
00:05:22,740 --> 00:05:24,550
I'll ask Officer Sato about it.

72
00:05:25,950 --> 00:05:29,450
Excuse me, Officer Sato. That ring...

73
00:05:31,650 --> 00:05:33,250
Sorry.

74
00:05:33,250 --> 00:05:35,660
I've found somebody I like.

75
00:05:35,660 --> 00:05:37,360
Miwa.

76
00:05:37,360 --> 00:05:38,960
Ms. Sato.

77
00:05:38,960 --> 00:05:39,960
Miwa.

78
00:05:42,760 --> 00:05:44,370
What's going on?

79
00:05:44,370 --> 00:05:47,340
Wearing it on her left ring finger means...

80
00:05:47,340 --> 00:05:48,640
She's engaged?

81
00:05:48,640 --> 00:05:51,240
That's what it means, isn't it? Hey!

82
00:05:51,240 --> 00:05:54,340
I'd sure like to know what it means.

83
00:05:54,340 --> 00:05:55,340
What?

84
00:05:55,340 --> 00:05:58,450
You mean that ring isn't what you gave her?

85
00:05:58,450 --> 00:05:59,450
No.

86
00:05:59,450 --> 00:06:02,550
I didn't buy it, nor have I seen it ever before.

87
00:06:02,550 --> 00:06:04,750
Then who on earth?

88
00:06:22,840 --> 00:06:24,240
Tozawa of the patrol division.

89
00:06:24,240 --> 00:06:25,940
Sonenaga of the crime prevention division.

90
00:06:25,940 --> 00:06:28,340
Taniguchi of the traffic and transportation division.

91
00:06:28,340 --> 00:06:30,650
I'm sorry. Could you hold a moment, please?

92
00:06:30,650 --> 00:06:31,750
Hey!

93
00:06:33,050 --> 00:06:34,050
Hey!

94
00:06:34,050 --> 00:06:36,550
Be quiet, will you?

95
00:06:36,550 --> 00:06:38,350
Please.

96
00:06:38,350 --> 00:06:39,750
Hello.

97
00:06:39,750 --> 00:06:41,860
I'm sorry. And then?

98
00:06:44,260 --> 00:06:45,360
What?

99
00:06:45,360 --> 00:06:46,660
Someone is...

100
00:06:46,660 --> 00:06:47,860
Someone is dead?

101
00:06:55,740 --> 00:06:57,540
I got it, Ran.

102
00:06:57,540 --> 00:06:59,040
I'll be right over.

103
00:07:01,640 --> 00:07:03,140
Officer Takagi! Let's go!

104
00:07:03,140 --> 00:07:04,350
What?

105
00:07:04,350 --> 00:07:06,450
There was a murder at a villa in Okutama!

106
00:07:06,450 --> 00:07:07,750
Officer Takagi!

107
00:07:07,750 --> 00:07:08,750
Yes, sir!

108
00:07:08,750 --> 00:07:11,450
I'm sorry, but could you take this?

109
00:07:11,450 --> 00:07:13,350
I would rather...

110
00:07:15,760 --> 00:07:17,760
I've got no choice, though.

111
00:07:17,760 --> 00:07:20,360
I've got my own problems, you know.

112
00:07:27,140 --> 00:07:29,340
It's a big problem!

113
00:07:33,690 --> 00:07:35,490
A bright step forward to a prosperous future.

114
00:07:35,490 --> 00:07:37,800
My heart is of course prepared for what is to come!

115
00:07:37,800 --> 00:07:40,600
A ring glitters on Officer Sato's left hand.

116
00:07:40,600 --> 00:07:42,400
Did Officer Takagi finally do it?

117
00:07:42,400 --> 00:07:43,800
He sees through the one and only truth.

118
00:07:43,800 --> 00:07:45,600
A child in appearance with the I.Q. of an adult.

119
00:07:45,600 --> 00:07:47,710
No case is left unsolved with Detective Conan.

120
00:09:30,690 --> 00:09:33,600
"Love Story at Police Headquarters 8".

121
00:09:33,600 --> 00:09:35,700
"Left Hand Ring Finger".

122
00:09:36,700 --> 00:09:40,100
"Half a day earlier" -What a fantastic ring.

123
00:09:40,100 --> 00:09:43,610
Look at the number of stones on it. Fabulous.

124
00:09:43,610 --> 00:09:45,710
Are they all diamonds?

125
00:09:47,080 --> 00:09:50,180
I've never seen anything like this before.

126
00:09:50,180 --> 00:09:51,980
That's right.

127
00:09:51,980 --> 00:09:53,380
It's a ring that I had custom made

128
00:09:53,380 --> 00:09:55,790
in memory of my 100th piece of work.

129
00:09:55,790 --> 00:09:58,890
It says "100th" on the back.

130
00:09:58,890 --> 00:10:01,190
"100th" -See.

131
00:10:01,190 --> 00:10:03,290
"Masutaka Moroguchi (52)" -I actually asked them to put

132
00:10:03,290 --> 00:10:05,200
"Mystery Author" -100 diamonds on the ring,

133
00:10:05,200 --> 00:10:06,500
but they told me that doing so

134
00:10:06,500 --> 00:10:08,600
would make the ring larger than a finger shield,

135
00:10:08,600 --> 00:10:10,500
so they were against it.

136
00:10:14,100 --> 00:10:15,710
I guess so.

137
00:10:19,910 --> 00:10:20,980
Excuse me.

138
00:10:20,980 --> 00:10:22,680
I'd like to switch the tape.

139
00:10:22,680 --> 00:10:25,880
But how unusual, in this day and age

140
00:10:25,880 --> 00:10:28,890
-to be using a cassette tape recorder. -Yes.

141
00:10:28,890 --> 00:10:30,590
"Kakuji Dejima (34)" -Nowadays most everything

142
00:10:30,590 --> 00:10:32,690
"Writer" -is recorded digitally,

143
00:10:32,690 --> 00:10:34,790
but I for some reason don't feel comfortable

144
00:10:34,790 --> 00:10:37,490
unless I see the tape spinning.

145
00:10:38,700 --> 00:10:39,900
In digital recording,

146
00:10:39,900 --> 00:10:42,900
errors are a problem too.

147
00:10:42,900 --> 00:10:44,700
I see.

148
00:10:44,700 --> 00:10:46,600
In fact, I feel the same, too.

149
00:10:48,110 --> 00:10:49,610
"Wataru Tarumi (33)" -All the other cameramen

150
00:10:49,610 --> 00:10:52,010
"Cameraman" -use digital cameras,

151
00:10:52,010 --> 00:10:56,280
but I just can't seem to let go of this old analogue camera

152
00:10:56,280 --> 00:10:58,080
that I've been using from before.

153
00:10:58,080 --> 00:11:01,390
Well, the only thing is, with this you can't see

154
00:11:01,390 --> 00:11:03,090
how the pictures come out right away.

155
00:11:06,190 --> 00:11:07,890
Hey, hey.

156
00:11:07,890 --> 00:11:09,690
I'm sorry I have to intrude on you

157
00:11:09,690 --> 00:11:11,090
when you're talking about analogue

158
00:11:11,090 --> 00:11:12,200
"Harue Anabuki (33)" -but Mr. Moroguchi

159
00:11:12,200 --> 00:11:13,500
"Magazine Editor" -needs to meet the deadline

160
00:11:13,500 --> 00:11:16,400
which is closing in for his current serial story, you know.

161
00:11:16,400 --> 00:11:18,300
I wish you'd stop quit idle talk

162
00:11:18,300 --> 00:11:20,500
and finish what you got to do.

163
00:11:20,500 --> 00:11:23,010
Come on, cool head, Ms. Anabuki.

164
00:11:23,010 --> 00:11:25,010
After all, Detective Mouri

165
00:11:25,010 --> 00:11:28,080
are going to be having the talk tomorrow.

166
00:11:30,380 --> 00:11:33,380
I'll make dinner tonight,

167
00:11:33,380 --> 00:11:35,090
have him rest well

168
00:11:35,090 --> 00:11:37,790
and tomorrow morning within the morning sun.

169
00:11:37,790 --> 00:11:39,690
Isn't that right, Mr. Writer?

170
00:11:39,690 --> 00:11:41,090
Yes.

171
00:11:41,090 --> 00:11:42,990
Well, you see,

172
00:11:42,990 --> 00:11:46,100
this is like an introductory rehearsal.

173
00:11:48,500 --> 00:11:50,800
On this month's preview page...

174
00:11:50,800 --> 00:11:53,900
See! There's a big ad that goes,

175
00:11:53,900 --> 00:11:55,610
"Writer Masutaka Moroguchi will have a talk out

176
00:11:55,610 --> 00:11:58,610
with famed Detective Kogoro Mouri,

177
00:11:58,610 --> 00:12:00,780
on the new dawn of mystery stories!"

178
00:12:00,780 --> 00:12:02,380
Please take a look at it.

179
00:12:03,480 --> 00:12:04,780
Let's see.

180
00:12:07,780 --> 00:12:09,690
What's the matter?

181
00:12:09,690 --> 00:12:11,490
You look puzzled.

182
00:12:13,590 --> 00:12:16,790
I just felt that he wasn't the kind of person I thought he was.

183
00:12:16,790 --> 00:12:20,100
By that, do you mean Mr. Moroguchi?

184
00:12:21,900 --> 00:12:24,900
Because his mystery story here

185
00:12:24,900 --> 00:12:27,800
is particular about little details.

186
00:12:27,800 --> 00:12:30,010
I was sure that he would be a nervous person

187
00:12:30,010 --> 00:12:33,110
who is always annoyed.

188
00:12:36,280 --> 00:12:37,680
Ms. Anabuki!

189
00:12:38,780 --> 00:12:39,880
Yes?

190
00:12:39,880 --> 00:12:42,590
Do you have a ruler?

191
00:12:42,590 --> 00:12:43,690
Yes.

192
00:12:43,690 --> 00:12:45,690
I have a tape measure with me.

193
00:12:50,690 --> 00:12:52,100
Just as I thought.

194
00:12:53,900 --> 00:12:55,200
The font of my name

195
00:12:55,200 --> 00:12:58,700
is 1 mm smaller than that of the other writers!

196
00:12:58,700 --> 00:13:00,800
Are you trying to humiliate me or something?

197
00:13:00,800 --> 00:13:02,610
No... no way.

198
00:13:02,610 --> 00:13:05,110
It's only that a font that size looks nicer

199
00:13:05,110 --> 00:13:06,810
and fits in much nicer, that's why.

200
00:13:06,810 --> 00:13:07,880
Then,

201
00:13:07,880 --> 00:13:10,480
why not make the fonts of the other writers smaller?

202
00:13:11,680 --> 00:13:13,580
You good-for-nothing!

203
00:13:16,790 --> 00:13:19,290
I'm sorry.

204
00:13:19,290 --> 00:13:22,190
I'll make sure that nothing like this happens again.

205
00:13:22,190 --> 00:13:23,690
Phooey! You'd better!

206
00:13:23,690 --> 00:13:25,200
I see.

207
00:13:25,200 --> 00:13:28,300
I guess he's nervous about everything else.

208
00:13:28,300 --> 00:13:29,600
Really.

209
00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:34,300
Mr. Akiba, the editor in charge before you was great.

210
00:13:34,300 --> 00:13:37,210
He granted my every wish.

211
00:13:38,910 --> 00:13:41,480
He must've been a capable editor.

212
00:13:42,580 --> 00:13:44,580
From looking for image data

213
00:13:44,580 --> 00:13:48,690
to investigating specialized knowledge regarding tricks...

214
00:13:48,690 --> 00:13:52,690
He spared no pains at serving me.

215
00:13:54,490 --> 00:13:58,100
I mean, until his life ran out on him.

216
00:14:02,900 --> 00:14:06,200
Did... did he die?

217
00:14:06,200 --> 00:14:10,810
This spring, he found dead at home

218
00:14:10,810 --> 00:14:14,780
in a room that was completely locked.

219
00:14:16,080 --> 00:14:17,980
Locked room?

220
00:14:17,980 --> 00:14:19,780
Did he commit suicide?

221
00:14:19,780 --> 00:14:21,890
I would think so.

222
00:14:21,890 --> 00:14:24,490
I mean, it's not one of the mystery stories I wrote, you know.

223
00:14:24,490 --> 00:14:30,290
In fact, I thought of writing a story based on his death,

224
00:14:30,290 --> 00:14:33,200
but Ms. Anabuki stopped me.

225
00:14:33,200 --> 00:14:34,800
Most naturally!

226
00:14:34,800 --> 00:14:36,300
The fact that he died suddenly

227
00:14:36,300 --> 00:14:39,300
is quite widespread, in the publishing business.

228
00:14:39,300 --> 00:14:42,010
Therefore, writing a novel about it

229
00:14:42,010 --> 00:14:46,510
would just make way for gossip articles.

230
00:14:46,510 --> 00:14:47,980
That's why I asked him not to.

231
00:14:47,980 --> 00:14:49,980
Gossip is gossip

232
00:14:49,980 --> 00:14:51,580
and not the truth.

233
00:14:51,580 --> 00:14:52,580
Besides,

234
00:14:52,580 --> 00:14:55,790
if it's entitled something like "A Tribute to Editor Akiba",

235
00:14:55,790 --> 00:14:58,890
maybe it would've sold, don't you think?

236
00:14:58,890 --> 00:15:00,890
Well...

237
00:15:04,590 --> 00:15:05,600
What...

238
00:15:07,000 --> 00:15:08,200
Oh, no.

239
00:15:08,200 --> 00:15:10,700
I'm out of lead.

240
00:15:10,700 --> 00:15:13,400
Would you like to use mine?

241
00:15:25,780 --> 00:15:29,990
But I use regular pencils.

242
00:15:29,990 --> 00:15:31,690
Even though it's analogue.

243
00:15:33,090 --> 00:15:35,590
Well, then. Thank you.

244
00:15:37,490 --> 00:15:39,000
Okay, let's just decide

245
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:42,000
on the course of action for tomorrow for now.

246
00:15:44,100 --> 00:15:47,100
After all, we're be filming tomorrow morning.

247
00:15:47,100 --> 00:15:49,710
Taking up time eating like this is doing us no good.

248
00:15:56,180 --> 00:15:58,380
Besides, I don't want to waste film.

249
00:16:06,190 --> 00:16:07,390
After that,

250
00:16:07,390 --> 00:16:11,390
talking over arrangements continued over dinner

251
00:16:11,390 --> 00:16:13,700
for two hours.

252
00:16:13,700 --> 00:16:17,100
We had no idea that all this work would amount to nothing.

253
00:16:17,100 --> 00:16:18,400
Right.

254
00:16:18,400 --> 00:16:22,410
Because the main character of the interview...

255
00:16:24,610 --> 00:16:26,310
Mr. Moroguchi?

256
00:16:26,310 --> 00:16:28,380
It's already 5:00 a.m!

257
00:16:29,580 --> 00:16:32,580
Mr. Moroguchi? Moroguchi!

258
00:16:33,680 --> 00:16:35,790
What's the matter?

259
00:16:35,790 --> 00:16:37,190
Mr. Mouri!

260
00:16:37,190 --> 00:16:39,390
Is he still asleep?

261
00:16:39,390 --> 00:16:40,390
Yes.

262
00:16:40,390 --> 00:16:44,390
Maybe he was working till late last night.

263
00:16:44,390 --> 00:16:46,000
Let's use a spare key to open the door

264
00:16:46,000 --> 00:16:47,200
and wake him up then!

265
00:16:47,200 --> 00:16:48,300
The thing is,

266
00:16:48,300 --> 00:16:53,100
Mr. Moroguchi hated for others to go into this room

267
00:16:53,100 --> 00:16:55,010
so there is no spare key.

268
00:16:55,010 --> 00:16:56,910
He said that he didn't want his works to be stolen.

269
00:16:56,910 --> 00:16:58,210
Hey, Conan.

270
00:16:58,210 --> 00:17:00,110
What're you doing?

271
00:17:04,680 --> 00:17:05,980
I have this bad premonition.

272
00:17:05,980 --> 00:17:07,280
Like something is pushing down on my chest.

273
00:17:07,280 --> 00:17:09,290
I feel like I'm having difficulty breathing.

274
00:17:10,390 --> 00:17:11,590
At times like this,

275
00:17:11,590 --> 00:17:13,490
almost without fail...

276
00:17:17,490 --> 00:17:20,500
It's been about an hour since he passed on.

277
00:17:22,600 --> 00:17:24,100
The odor of almond.

278
00:17:24,100 --> 00:17:26,200
Cyanide type poison.

279
00:17:26,200 --> 00:17:29,110
The stuff around his mouth is coffee.

280
00:17:29,110 --> 00:17:31,510
Was the poison mixed in his drink?

281
00:17:35,080 --> 00:17:37,980
The room was locked completely.

282
00:17:37,980 --> 00:17:39,580
The only place that was open

283
00:17:39,580 --> 00:17:42,390
was the place I used to come in here.

284
00:17:42,390 --> 00:17:43,890
Just that ventilation window,

285
00:17:43,890 --> 00:17:46,590
only big enough for a child to barely make it through.

286
00:17:47,490 --> 00:17:50,990
The thing that he is holding in his hand

287
00:17:50,990 --> 00:17:52,500
is probably the key to this room.

288
00:17:52,500 --> 00:17:54,600
Is it suicide?

289
00:17:54,600 --> 00:17:58,100
No. This is...

290
00:17:58,100 --> 00:17:59,900
murder?

291
00:18:05,100 --> 00:18:07,400
The victim is a mystery novelist,

292
00:18:07,400 --> 00:18:10,110
Mr. Masutaka Moroguchi, age 52.

293
00:18:10,110 --> 00:18:12,610
The cause of death is suffocation

294
00:18:12,610 --> 00:18:14,110
due to cyanide poisoning.

295
00:18:14,110 --> 00:18:17,110
From the coffee that is left around his mouth,

296
00:18:17,110 --> 00:18:18,210
he most likely...

297
00:18:18,210 --> 00:18:22,020
Mixed cyanide into his drink and drank it

298
00:18:22,020 --> 00:18:25,120
or, somebody made him drink it.

299
00:18:26,490 --> 00:18:27,590
What is it?

300
00:18:27,590 --> 00:18:30,690
I don't think anyone made him drink it.

301
00:18:30,690 --> 00:18:32,390
Because the door and windows of this room

302
00:18:32,390 --> 00:18:34,500
were completely locked.

303
00:18:34,500 --> 00:18:36,600
It was indeed a locked room.

304
00:18:36,600 --> 00:18:39,300
Moreover, Mr. Moroguchi is holding

305
00:18:39,300 --> 00:18:40,700
the key to this room in his hand,

306
00:18:40,700 --> 00:18:42,200
and neither is there a spare key.

307
00:18:42,200 --> 00:18:43,610
Taking all these things into consideration,

308
00:18:43,610 --> 00:18:46,010
suicide is the only thinkable conclusion, isn't it?

309
00:18:46,010 --> 00:18:47,710
Why would it be so?

310
00:18:47,710 --> 00:18:49,910
If someone put cyanide

311
00:18:49,910 --> 00:18:52,910
into his coffee cup beforehand,

312
00:18:52,910 --> 00:18:55,320
wouldn't a locked room murder be possible?

313
00:18:55,320 --> 00:18:57,320
Of course, that's if someone knew

314
00:18:57,320 --> 00:19:02,090
that Mr. Moroguchi drinks coffee after getting up in the morning.

315
00:19:02,090 --> 00:19:03,790
Idiot!

316
00:19:03,790 --> 00:19:05,390
A person normally doesn't drink coffee

317
00:19:05,390 --> 00:19:07,400
holding a key in his hand, does he?

318
00:19:07,400 --> 00:19:09,800
Of course, it would be impossible to grab the key

319
00:19:09,800 --> 00:19:11,100
even if he were to have realized

320
00:19:11,100 --> 00:19:13,900
that he had drunk poisoned coffee.

321
00:19:13,900 --> 00:19:15,100
So, it's most probable

322
00:19:15,100 --> 00:19:19,410
that he held the key before drinking the poisoned coffee.

323
00:19:19,410 --> 00:19:22,010
So, it must be some kind of message from him.

324
00:19:22,010 --> 00:19:24,810
But wasn't Mr. Moroguchi scheduled to have

325
00:19:24,810 --> 00:19:28,020
a talk show with you this morning, Mr. Mouri?

326
00:19:29,820 --> 00:19:30,820
If so,

327
00:19:30,820 --> 00:19:33,190
maybe he overslept, and in his haste, picked up the key

328
00:19:33,190 --> 00:19:34,590
before leaving the room then,

329
00:19:34,590 --> 00:19:38,890
sipped a cup of coffee to wake himself up, right?

330
00:19:38,890 --> 00:19:41,700
For God's sake, take a good look!

331
00:19:42,700 --> 00:19:45,800
The coffee cup was on the floor beside the bed.

332
00:19:45,800 --> 00:19:47,700
Yes, that's true.

333
00:19:49,200 --> 00:19:52,810
The coffee maker's in the kitchen over that side.

334
00:19:52,810 --> 00:19:54,010
If he were in a rush,

335
00:19:54,010 --> 00:19:56,210
wouldn't he have made the coffee in the kitchen

336
00:19:56,210 --> 00:19:58,210
and drunk it then and there?

337
00:19:58,210 --> 00:19:59,810
He would never put the cup on a saucer,

338
00:19:59,810 --> 00:20:03,120
take it his bed and drink it!

339
00:20:03,120 --> 00:20:05,990
But what if it were this way?

340
00:20:05,990 --> 00:20:08,690
Somebody who came to wake Mr. Moroguchi up,

341
00:20:08,690 --> 00:20:11,690
made coffee mixed with cyanide

342
00:20:11,690 --> 00:20:13,800
and put it beside his bed.

343
00:20:13,800 --> 00:20:17,100
Then told him to hurry, made him hold the key

344
00:20:17,100 --> 00:20:18,800
and left the room?

345
00:20:18,800 --> 00:20:20,600
Not possible.

346
00:20:20,600 --> 00:20:23,610
If so, that someone

347
00:20:23,610 --> 00:20:25,510
would've had to leave the room

348
00:20:25,510 --> 00:20:27,810
before Mr. Moroguchi drank the coffee,

349
00:20:27,810 --> 00:20:30,810
and make him lock the door.

350
00:20:30,810 --> 00:20:32,610
This sounds pretty impossible.

351
00:20:32,610 --> 00:20:34,320
Whether or not a person drinks the coffee

352
00:20:34,320 --> 00:20:36,520
that is served right away, depends on the person.

353
00:20:36,520 --> 00:20:38,420
But if he were rushed,

354
00:20:38,420 --> 00:20:40,790
he probably would've drunk it.

355
00:20:40,790 --> 00:20:43,890
It could be that Mr. Moroguchi didn't like hot stuff

356
00:20:43,890 --> 00:20:46,790
and didn't drink his coffee right away.

357
00:20:46,790 --> 00:20:48,200
No way!

358
00:20:49,700 --> 00:20:52,700
Mr. Moroguchi liked coffee very much

359
00:20:52,700 --> 00:20:54,400
so whether it was hot or warm,

360
00:20:54,400 --> 00:20:58,310
he would drink it saying it was delicious.

361
00:20:58,310 --> 00:21:00,310
Isn't that right?

362
00:21:00,310 --> 00:21:01,310
Yes.

363
00:21:01,310 --> 00:21:03,210
Everybody knew about it in the editing room.

364
00:21:04,910 --> 00:21:07,520
And who are you?

365
00:21:07,520 --> 00:21:08,520
Yes.

366
00:21:08,520 --> 00:21:12,990
I'm Anabuki in charge of editing for Mr. Moroguchi.

367
00:21:12,990 --> 00:21:14,290
The two behind me,

368
00:21:14,290 --> 00:21:16,690
are to the right, cameraman, Mr. Tarumi,

369
00:21:16,690 --> 00:21:19,590
and to the left, Mr. Dejima, a writer.

370
00:21:19,590 --> 00:21:23,200
Did you three come here to make plans

371
00:21:23,200 --> 00:21:26,800
on the talk show this morning?

372
00:21:26,800 --> 00:21:29,100
No, all three of us

373
00:21:29,100 --> 00:21:30,810
spent the night here from last night.

374
00:21:30,810 --> 00:21:33,610
I mean, it's kind of tough trying to get here

375
00:21:33,610 --> 00:21:36,110
before 5:00 in the morning, so...

376
00:21:36,110 --> 00:21:37,810
But, how strange.

377
00:21:39,110 --> 00:21:40,620
If the room were locked,

378
00:21:40,620 --> 00:21:41,920
you'd most likely break the door down

379
00:21:41,920 --> 00:21:44,320
or crack the window,

380
00:21:44,320 --> 00:21:46,990
but there are no such traces.

381
00:21:46,990 --> 00:21:49,390
How did you make it into the room?

382
00:21:49,390 --> 00:21:53,390
This brat did it! Phooey!

383
00:21:55,900 --> 00:21:58,800
Conan went in through that ventilation window over there,

384
00:21:58,800 --> 00:22:02,000
and opened the door from the inside for us,

385
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:03,910
and we got in.

386
00:22:03,910 --> 00:22:08,010
That's when we found Mr. Moroguchi dead.

387
00:22:08,010 --> 00:22:10,510
Which means that the window was open?

388
00:22:10,510 --> 00:22:12,610
Yes, that's right.

389
00:22:12,610 --> 00:22:14,820
But it's only wide enough

390
00:22:14,820 --> 00:22:16,520
for a child to get through, isn't it?

391
00:22:16,520 --> 00:22:19,320
Let's assume that it was suicide.

392
00:22:19,320 --> 00:22:20,690
Yet, why would Mr. Moroguchi die

393
00:22:20,690 --> 00:22:23,690
holding the key in his hand?

394
00:22:23,690 --> 00:22:27,000
Maybe the culprit didn't want all of us here at the villa

395
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:31,500
to be suspected of murder.

396
00:22:31,500 --> 00:22:32,800
Like I just said,

397
00:22:32,800 --> 00:22:35,300
if this were murder,

398
00:22:35,300 --> 00:22:37,110
unless the culprit said something like,

399
00:22:37,110 --> 00:22:40,010
"Drink your coffee while holding your key and lock the door..."

400
00:22:40,010 --> 00:22:42,810
This situation would be hard to create.

401
00:22:42,810 --> 00:22:44,210
And?

402
00:22:44,210 --> 00:22:45,410
Would you have any idea as to why Mr. Moroguchi

403
00:22:45,410 --> 00:22:46,610
would want to commit suicide?

404
00:22:46,610 --> 00:22:49,120
No. Not that I know of.

405
00:22:49,120 --> 00:22:52,220
He didn't show any such signs, did he?

406
00:22:52,220 --> 00:22:55,390
No, not at all.

407
00:22:55,390 --> 00:22:57,890
Well, maybe he had a lot of things on his mind

408
00:22:57,890 --> 00:22:59,990
that he couldn't tell others.

409
00:22:59,990 --> 00:23:01,500
It seems that the previous editor,

410
00:23:01,500 --> 00:23:03,600
Mr. Akiba, who was in charge of him

411
00:23:03,600 --> 00:23:06,100
committed suicide this spring too.

412
00:23:06,100 --> 00:23:10,410
It could be that he felt seriously responsible for what happened.

413
00:23:13,110 --> 00:23:15,110
At any rate,

414
00:23:15,110 --> 00:23:18,210
let's wait for the forensic officer to arrive.

415
00:23:18,210 --> 00:23:20,010
If this is homicide,

416
00:23:20,010 --> 00:23:21,720
the fingerprints of the culprit

417
00:23:21,720 --> 00:23:23,420
has to be somewhere here.

418
00:23:23,420 --> 00:23:26,590
If the culprit wore gloves when serving coffee

419
00:23:26,590 --> 00:23:28,390
or when opening and closing the door,

420
00:23:28,390 --> 00:23:30,890
I'm sure it would breed suspicion in Mr. Moroguchi too.

421
00:23:30,890 --> 00:23:32,490
Besides, if the door was locked,

422
00:23:32,490 --> 00:23:34,700
the culprit wouldn't have had time to wipe anything off.

423
00:23:34,700 --> 00:23:37,600
That is, if none of you touched anything

424
00:23:37,600 --> 00:23:40,000
before I got here.

425
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:43,300
No, because Detective Mouri warned us not to touch anything

426
00:23:43,300 --> 00:23:46,210
until the police got here.

427
00:23:46,210 --> 00:23:48,210
I'm sure this is a suicide case,

428
00:23:48,210 --> 00:23:50,510
no need to call the forensic officers.

429
00:23:50,510 --> 00:23:52,510
Officer Takagi.

430
00:23:54,320 --> 00:23:56,420
Doesn't it bother you?

431
00:23:56,420 --> 00:23:58,020
What do you mean?

432
00:23:58,020 --> 00:23:59,790
The ring!

433
00:24:00,990 --> 00:24:03,490
What? What're you talking about? Conan!

434
00:24:03,490 --> 00:24:05,890
Well, of course it'd be a lie

435
00:24:05,890 --> 00:24:07,200
if I said it didn't bother me,

436
00:24:07,200 --> 00:24:10,200
but now we're in the middle of an investigation.

437
00:24:12,200 --> 00:24:13,500
No!

438
00:24:15,500 --> 00:24:18,410
Where are you looking? Over here!

439
00:24:18,410 --> 00:24:20,610
This man's ring.

440
00:24:20,610 --> 00:24:24,210
The number 100 that's carved is upside down.

441
00:24:26,510 --> 00:24:27,720
Right,

442
00:24:27,720 --> 00:24:30,720
but he could've just put it on upside down by mistake.

443
00:24:30,720 --> 00:24:34,290
But this man was a very nervous person,

444
00:24:34,290 --> 00:24:37,290
so I don't think he'd make such a mistake.

445
00:24:37,290 --> 00:24:39,090
Besides, this ring...

446
00:24:42,400 --> 00:24:45,400
See! There're so many diamonds on it.

447
00:24:46,900 --> 00:24:49,100
Oh, I see!

448
00:24:49,100 --> 00:24:51,010
So this is a homicide case after all!

449
00:24:51,010 --> 00:24:52,510
What?

450
00:24:52,510 --> 00:24:56,110
The reason he was killed was because of this ring!

451
00:24:56,110 --> 00:24:58,810
The culprit switched the ring with the genuine stones on it

452
00:24:58,810 --> 00:25:00,410
with a fake one

453
00:25:00,410 --> 00:25:03,020
and when the culprit put the fake back on Mr. Moroguchi's finger,

454
00:25:03,020 --> 00:25:06,220
he put it on upside down in his haste!

455
00:25:06,220 --> 00:25:10,090
Did Mr. Moroguchi ever take this ring off?

456
00:25:10,090 --> 00:25:13,190
No. He liked it very much,

457
00:25:13,190 --> 00:25:16,500
so much so that he used to wear it

458
00:25:16,500 --> 00:25:20,200
even when taking a bath and going to bed.

459
00:25:20,200 --> 00:25:23,400
Then, just as Officer Takagi says,

460
00:25:23,400 --> 00:25:26,110
there is a high probability that this is a case of homicide.

461
00:25:26,110 --> 00:25:29,510
So, another mystery has emerged.

462
00:25:29,510 --> 00:25:30,710
I see.

463
00:25:30,710 --> 00:25:33,410
The only time the culprit could've switched the ring

464
00:25:33,410 --> 00:25:36,020
is after Mr. Moroguchi died.

465
00:25:36,020 --> 00:25:40,190
And most naturally, the culprit was in this room at that time.

466
00:25:40,190 --> 00:25:41,690
If so,

467
00:25:41,690 --> 00:25:46,290
how did the culprit escape from this locked room?

468
00:25:46,290 --> 00:25:50,600
How on earth, after leaving the key in Mr. Moroguchi's hand?

469
00:25:50,600 --> 00:25:53,900
Or is it that after poisoning Mr. Moroguchi,

470
00:25:53,900 --> 00:25:57,310
the culprit left this room and locked the door,

471
00:25:57,310 --> 00:26:00,110
and in some way returned the key

472
00:26:00,110 --> 00:26:03,010
into Mr. Moroguchi's hand from outside?

473
00:26:03,010 --> 00:26:07,420
Only that ventilation window was open.

474
00:26:07,420 --> 00:26:08,820
There's nearly 4 meters from over there

475
00:26:08,820 --> 00:26:10,920
to the hand of the corpse.

476
00:26:13,390 --> 00:26:18,390
It's too far to do something like that.

477
00:26:24,190 --> 00:26:25,890
Okay,

478
00:26:25,890 --> 00:26:27,560
while we're waiting for the forensic officers to arrive,

479
00:26:27,560 --> 00:26:29,760
I'd like you to answer my questions.

480
00:26:29,760 --> 00:26:32,560
I would like to know where all of you were

481
00:26:32,560 --> 00:26:33,760
and what you were doing

482
00:26:33,760 --> 00:26:35,770
before finding Mr. Moroguchi's dead body.

483
00:26:35,770 --> 00:26:37,670
First, let's start with you, Mr. Dejima.

484
00:26:37,670 --> 00:26:39,970
I... I was in my room

485
00:26:39,970 --> 00:26:42,670
fixing this tape recorder.

486
00:26:42,670 --> 00:26:44,480
Something seems to be wrong with it.

487
00:26:44,480 --> 00:26:46,880
The tape inside is all wrinkled

488
00:26:46,880 --> 00:26:48,280
and when I try to rewind it...

489
00:26:48,280 --> 00:26:50,280
See! This is how it sounds.

490
00:26:52,080 --> 00:26:55,590
True. It does sound funny.

491
00:26:55,590 --> 00:26:57,690
Next. How about you, Mr. Tarumi?

492
00:26:57,690 --> 00:27:00,860
After I finishing setting things up for shooting,

493
00:27:00,860 --> 00:27:01,860
I returned to my room

494
00:27:01,860 --> 00:27:04,960
and was organizing the negatives for a different job.

495
00:27:04,960 --> 00:27:06,860
I bundled them up with this rubber band.

496
00:27:07,870 --> 00:27:09,270
Okay.

497
00:27:09,270 --> 00:27:11,870
Then, next Ms. Anabuki.

498
00:27:11,870 --> 00:27:13,370
I was also in my room

499
00:27:13,370 --> 00:27:16,270
looking over the draft of another writer.

500
00:27:16,270 --> 00:27:17,880
Ms. Anabuki.

501
00:27:17,880 --> 00:27:19,980
You had a metal tape on you, didn't you?

502
00:27:19,980 --> 00:27:22,180
Do you always carry it around?

503
00:27:22,180 --> 00:27:23,780
What? Yes.

504
00:27:23,780 --> 00:27:25,580
Because Mr. Moroguchi usually tells me

505
00:27:25,580 --> 00:27:29,290
to measure things, like the size of the fonts.

506
00:27:29,290 --> 00:27:30,990
But if it's to measure the fonts,

507
00:27:30,990 --> 00:27:32,890
won't a ruler do?

508
00:27:32,890 --> 00:27:35,160
Hey, Sonny.

509
00:27:35,160 --> 00:27:36,960
She not only had to measure fonts,

510
00:27:36,960 --> 00:27:40,260
but all kinds of other stuff too.

511
00:27:40,260 --> 00:27:41,870
Like doors and windows

512
00:27:41,870 --> 00:27:44,170
that were likely to be used as tricks.

513
00:27:44,170 --> 00:27:46,570
You sure know a lot.

514
00:27:46,570 --> 00:27:50,070
The late Akiba used to tell me all these things.

515
00:27:50,070 --> 00:27:51,780
All three of us

516
00:27:51,780 --> 00:27:53,580
joined the company together with Mr. Akiba, so...

517
00:27:53,580 --> 00:27:55,580
I quit partway

518
00:27:55,580 --> 00:27:57,680
and became a free-lance writer though.

519
00:27:57,680 --> 00:28:00,990
I see. Is that right?

520
00:28:00,990 --> 00:28:04,390
Officer Sato...

521
00:28:04,390 --> 00:28:06,660
It has nothing to do with the case, but...

522
00:28:06,660 --> 00:28:08,660
What is it, Ran?

523
00:28:10,760 --> 00:28:12,560
That's probably the forensic officer.

524
00:28:12,560 --> 00:28:14,370
I'm sorry, Ran.

525
00:28:14,370 --> 00:28:15,770
Could you wait till later?

526
00:28:17,770 --> 00:28:19,870
Sure.

527
00:28:23,770 --> 00:28:25,280
It's genuine?

528
00:28:25,280 --> 00:28:27,980
That ring was genuine?

529
00:28:27,980 --> 00:28:29,080
Yes, ma'am.

530
00:28:29,080 --> 00:28:30,680
It was brought back to the station

531
00:28:30,680 --> 00:28:32,780
and taken to an appraiser right away,

532
00:28:32,780 --> 00:28:34,490
so there's no doubt about it.

533
00:28:34,490 --> 00:28:38,390
Which means, the culprit wasn't after the ring.

534
00:28:38,390 --> 00:28:40,560
Yes, that's right.

535
00:28:40,560 --> 00:28:42,360
Then, why?

536
00:28:42,360 --> 00:28:46,260
For what reason did the culprit remove the ring?

537
00:28:47,460 --> 00:28:49,470
And when the ring was removed,

538
00:28:49,470 --> 00:28:51,370
there was a strange trace left behind.

539
00:28:51,370 --> 00:28:52,870
A strange trace?

540
00:28:52,870 --> 00:28:54,070
Yes, ma'am.

541
00:28:54,070 --> 00:28:55,970
Over here.

542
00:28:55,970 --> 00:28:58,180
Although it seems to be a very old mark...

543
00:28:58,180 --> 00:29:01,380
It's a round, black mark.

544
00:29:01,380 --> 00:29:03,180
I wonder if it's a trace of blood?

545
00:29:03,180 --> 00:29:04,780
Blood...

546
00:29:04,780 --> 00:29:07,380
Why would there be blood here?

547
00:29:07,380 --> 00:29:09,290
He could've been shaving

548
00:29:09,290 --> 00:29:11,090
and cut himself pretty deep.

549
00:29:11,090 --> 00:29:15,160
Then he may have touched the place.

550
00:29:15,160 --> 00:29:19,060
See, there's a cut spot under his right jaw.

551
00:29:19,060 --> 00:29:21,070
No doubt about it.

552
00:29:21,070 --> 00:29:22,270
